**Searchable Description:**

This document discusses the preprocessing and augmentation of a chicken disease detection dataset initially obtained from Kaggle. The dataset faced a class imbalance issue, particularly with the Non-Contagious Disease (NCD) class, which initially had only 376 images. Augmentation techniques such as rotation, zooming, flipping, brightness adjustment, and slight distortion were applied to increase the NCD class to 1501 images, improving model robustness. The dataset was split into 80% training and 20% testing. The document outlines the training process using models like Vision Transformer, Swin Transformer, VGG19, EfficientNetB7, and MobileNetV3. Evaluation metrics include accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score. A majority voting scheme is used for final predictions. The document includes figures illustrating the dataset distribution and model architecture, with four fecal classes: Salmonella, Newcastle, Healthy, and Coccidiosis. The study is part of ICCA 2024, held in Dhaka, Bangladesh.

- Training uses the Adamax optimizer with a learning rate of 0.001 and categorical cross-entropy loss. Accuracy is the evaluation metric.
